<font color="#FF0000">BEING COOL IN NAM</font><br>
<tt>Sun Sep 14 13:19:37 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
<br>
I would have loved to have been on your chopper, but we probably would have both ended up in the brig, bag full of candy and all. Of course I would have ripped off your cool sunglasses before jumping off and even you wouldn't been able to find me in the jungle. <br>
I realized when I got to Nam that it was in a ways also a cool war, chopper pilots wearing sunray sunglasses of the latest design. Little Kids selling watches with BIG heads at only $5.00 each. Every pilot in Nam wore one of those.  So, what if they only lasted a week or a month. Cool colorful Camouflaged shorts, and poncho liners, funny looking MPC, funny looking bananas. Hanoi Hanna singing to us and offering us a good night kiss. American Armed Forces Radio waking us up in the morning with a Gooooooooood Moooorning Vieeet -NAM and playing for us the sounds of Steve Wonder singing  about our &quot;Place in the Sun.&quot;<br><br>
I remember Marty coming back from the states wearing funky colorful orange, and brown colored stripped pants. We though he had stolen them off a cool chopper pilot or a gay Naval officer.  Grunts aren't suppose to be able to tell the difference. All Marty could say when he got back was that &quot;Everything is psychedelic, and lots of mini skirts.&quot; back in the world.<br><br>
Go Go dancers at the USO show. Saw only one in Nam. Where did you guys get those cool sunglasses from. I would have traded you an AK for a pair. I think I did, even got a .38 pistol and shoulder hostler in the deal. But I was cool after that. Of course I bought them during the monsoon season when the price was down. <br><br>
There I was in the middle of Nam, with my cool sunglasses on, Cool long side-burns ELVIS style. Shoulder strapped .38 pistol wrapped around my skinny bare chest, a hundred rounds of M60 machine gun ammo strapped across the other way Poncho Villa style,  wearing my BIG watch, Camouflaged shorts. Holding the M60 machine gun with one hand, a Camel cigarrette in the other, standing near Liberty Bridge, with Dodge City in the background. Still have that picture, think I'll put it on the cover of the book.<br>

<p><code>-- Ed, I'll autograph and send you a copy  (Sparrowhawk) </code><p>


